ξ 25. lt is usual to enumerate, as a third naturai mode of acquisition, specificatio, the'converting of another's material into a new form or ‘species’ as in the illustratione given in tbe text. The Proculians argued the case on the analogy of occupatio, and regarded the giver of the form as the owner of the product; aview which seems to bave commended itself to Ulpian (‘ mutata forma prope interimit substantiam rei’ Dig. ro. 4 u 3). The Sabinians viewed itas a kind of accessio, and denied any transfer of ownership, Gaius ii. 99. The intennediate opinion, confirmed by Justinian, is found in Gaius (Dig. 41. 1. 77), Paulus (ib. 24), aad other jurists.
